title: HETEROFLEXIBILITY!! Jonah and Cyrus!! (PLEASE READ!!)
body:
I once watched this AMAZING film on YouTube about heteroflexibility, and I, unfortunately don’t remember the title (which makes me really depressed, like ugh) but anyways, I don’t know why I thought of this out of the blue, but the film reminded me of Cyrus and Jonah. If Cyrus were to ever come out and tell Jonah that he use to like him, I feel like Jonah wouldn’t be totally weirded out at the Idea of dating Cyrus. Now, this is just my opinion, but I truly believe that Jonah is 100% straight, BUT…because Jonah cares for Cyrus, and wants to see Cyrus happy, he would consider turning their friendship into a relationship. Heteroflexibility is basically when you aren’t necessarily gay or bisexual, but in between bi and straight. Like, being straight, but you would consider doing something with a member of the same gender should the situation arise. I also know that it can be called bent, but I prefer heteroflexibility. It DOESN’T mean that that person is gay, it just mean that they care so much for that same sex person, that feelings could switch into something more than platonic.

I think it would be really cute if Jonah was like, “you know how they say who would you go gay for? Well, that’d be you.” (I know this would NEVER happen because it’s DISNEY CHANNEL)

I’m sorry if your completely confused. I’m really bad at wording things, but the main point is that Jonah could just be a heteroflexible.

blog.title: Meta, Analysis, and Speculation
blog.description: I'm Dave (he/him). I'm a fan of Andi Mack, Riverdale, and Girl Meets World, and other shows and movies. Feel free to send me asks!

summary: Luke says we can expect “a lot of craziness happening with TJ, especially in his mind and with other people.” The latter half of...
question: Luke says we can expect “a lot of craziness happening with TJ, especially in his mind and with other people.” The latter half of that sounds Tyrus related, but any ideas on what the “mind” part might be about? The dyscalculia plotline? Sexuality (on second thought, probably not)? Something else entirely?
answer:
It won’t be related to his sexuality, that’s simply not in the show’s dna. However, it may provide the angst that the gay story line won’t be allowed to. It’s very hard to tell because this is almost certainly not something the writers planned for in S2 so there likely aren’t many if any hints. It’s very unusual for one recurring character to get so much development and they’ve already given him a learning disability. Anything too severe starts tipping TJ into a sort of ‘tragic gay’ trope. We can guess from when Josh first brought it up that it happens or at least starts in 3a and if both Josh and Luke can hint at it it’s likely not meant to be some huge shocking twist.

There’s a pretty broad spectrum of mental health story lines the show has done from Amber just needing someone to talk to and confide in to Jonah having multiple panic attacks. It’s hard to imagine Disney approving a big mental health story line for TJ especially since he’s a gay recurring character tied to Cyrus who’s plot lines in general are either non-existent or get short thrift. That Andi has yet to learn about Jonah’s panic attacks and Jonah has yet to get real treatment for them suggests that the show is going to circle back to that story line in a big way which also suggests that TJ’s plot line would be less intensive.

It could be something like TJ learning how to cope with stress or express emotions better; kind of unpacking the effects toxic masculinity can have. I could see the show at some point focusing on body image issues, they affect a lot of kids and it would be a bold choice to focus on body image issues that boys can have but as this is a show targeted to young girls I could see the writers deciding that giving a body image issues story line to one of the female characters could have more of an impact. Maybe TJ has a phobia? Something like a fear of dogs/heights/thunder and Cyrus can help him overcome it. 

For more serious mental health issues it could be something like depression but I don’t know if that’s too far for Disney and realistically if any character on this show is depressed it would be Cyrus, who’s also the one character whose mental health issues are largely treated as a joke. ADHD might be something Disney would allow but it doesn’t seem to fit with what we’ve seen of TJ, he seems to be able to focus just fine at work and on the team. OCD would be interesting but again we don’t know Disney’s restrictions. Anger management issues run the risk of making the audience afraid for both Cyrus and the kids who TJ works with and doesn’t seem to fit with his past approach to setbacks which is to generally be sulky and run away from his problems. 

I’ve mentioned before that part of the reason this will be the last season is that the gay story line is going to reach the hard limits of what Disney will allow but I also think that will hold true for other story lines as well. The Quinn/Mack family story line is likely going to delve perilously close into the circumstances of Andi’s birth and early life. And it’s likely that Jonah’s mental health story line and TJ’s mental health story line as well as whatever other mental health story lines they do will also reach the limits of what Disney is willing to approve.
